Recap:
St. Andrew's opened the 2025-26 season with a hard-fought 50-40 win over Morgan County at the Pro Movement Showcase at Eagles Landing Christian Academy in McDonough, Georgia.

The Lions scored the first eight points of the game and led throughout the entire first half, although the Bulldogs never allowed the margin to grow beyond eight.

In the second half Morgan County briefly grabbed a 40-39 lead with 4:27 remaining, but foul trouble proved costly down the stretch. St. Andrew's closed the game on an 11-0 run to seal the win.

Ja'Cari Glover led all scorers with 17 points and 11 rebounds despite dealing with foul trouble late in the first half. Page Getter added 13 points and 11 rebounds, going 9-for-13 from the free throw line, while Patrick Jackson provided a crucial spark off the bench with 8 points, 6 rebounds, and 4 steals.

Morgan County was led by Trey Carter with 13 points.

Both teams were playing their first game of the season, and the Lions will host South Effingham in their home opener next.

St. Andrews moved to 20 on the season with an emphatic 7746 win over the South Effingham Mustangs on Tuesday night at home. The Lions wasted no time asserting control, scoring the first 11 points of the game and racing out to a commanding 5118 halftime lead.

JaCari Glover delivered another standout performance, leading all scorers with 27 points while pulling down 11 rebounds, completing his second double-double in as many games. Chase Brown provided a major spark off the bench, knocking down three 3-pointers on his way to 13 points and adding 9 rebounds, finishing just shy of the first double-double of his career. Page Getter contributed 8 points and 5 rebounds, while Milos Copic and Guus Blom chipped in 7 points apiece. 

South Effingham was led by Michael Hall, who scored 21 points. 

With the win, the Lions improve to 20 on the season, while the Mustangs fall to 12. St. Andrews will be back in action on Friday when they host Bradwell Institute at 7 p.m.

St. Andrews battled hard but ultimately came up short on Friday night, falling 6850 to the Bradwell Institute Tigers. The Lions kept the game tight through much of the first half, trailing just 2118 with four minutes remaining in the second quarter. However, Bradwell closed the half on a decisive 100 run, seizing momentum and controlling the game from that point forward. 

The Tigers showcased a balanced offensive attack, with four players finishing in double figures. Christopher Perry led the way for Bradwell with 22 points, pacing an offense that proved difficult for the Lions to slow down. 

Despite the loss, JaCari Glover delivered another standout performance, finishing with 21 points and 13 rebounds to record his third double-double of the season. His strong effort kept St. Andrews within reach early, but the Lions were unable to overcome Bradwells late-half surge and second-half control. 

With the loss, the Lions move to 21 on the season. St. Andrews now turns its attention to a road matchup on December 2nd, when they travel to South Carolina to take on Hilton Head Island High School.

Lions Earn Gritty Road-Style Win Over Hilton Head Island, Improve to 31 

St. Andrews earned its toughest victory of the young season on Tuesday night, holding off the Hilton Head Island Seahawks 5653 in a tense finish that wasnt secure until the final buzzer. The win moves the Lions to 31, while the Seahawks drop to 11.

Hilton Head responded in the third period, using a strong run to take a 3937 lead into the fourth quarter. The final period featured multiple ties and lead changes as both teams traded defensive stops and key plays. 

With the game tied at 4545, St. Andrews produced several crucial stops and surged ahead 5247 entering the closing minutes. Hilton Head continued to battle and trimmed the deficit to one possession in the final seconds. The Seahawks called timeout with 2.6 seconds remaining, set up a final sideline inbound, and advanced the ball into the frontcourtbut were unable to get a shot off before the buzzer, securing the Lions 5653 win. 

JaCari Glover led the Lions with 16 points and 10 rebounds, earning his fourth double-double of the season. Page Getter delivered a strong all-around effort with 10 points and 8 rebounds, giving St. Andrews consistent lift throughout the night. Amari Cook added 9 points, 4 rebounds, and 4 assists from the point guard position. Chase Brown contributed 6 points and 5 rebounds, while Patrick Jackson chipped in 6 points to add a spark off the bench. 

A defining factor in the victory was St. Andrews dominance inside. The Lions held a 3632 advantage in points in the paint and controlled the boards with a decisive 3822 rebounding edge, including 18 offensive rebounds that generated key second-chance opportunities. That interior presence proved critical in a tight, possession-by-possession battle. 

St. Andrews will next be in action on Friday when they travel to Riverdale, GA, to take on New Faith Christian Academy.

Playing at home in the annual Gray Solana Memorial Game, St. Andrews delivered a strong response on Friday night, pulling away after halftime for a 6642 win over Hilton Head Prep.

The win marked an important bounce-back effort for St. Andrews after dropping its previous two games. With the victory, the Lions improve to 43 on the season, while Hilton Head Prep falls to 32.

RecapTitle: Balanced Attack Lifts St. Andrews Past Mount Paran at Christmas Classic

RecapTitle: Lions Grind Out 5046 Win Over Effingham County

Effingham County briefly seized control in the third quarter, pushing ahead 3531, but St. Andrews responded with a timely run to pull even and prevent the game from slipping away. That response proved pivotal, as the Lions entered the fourth quarter with renewed energy and focus.

RecapTitle: Glovers Double-Double Powers Lions to Third Straight Win
Recap:

RecapTitle: St. Andrews Rolls Past Pinewood in Region Opener
Recap:
St. Andrews opened region play in dominant fashion Friday night, rolling past Pinewood Christian 6821 in an away contest to begin the region schedule with authority. The win marked the Lions opening region game of the season, as they look to extend a remarkable run of four consecutive undefeated region campaigns and keep their region record spotless for a fifth straight year.

From the opening tip, St. Andrews set the tone on both ends of the floor. The Lions jumped out quickly, applying defensive pressure and converting high-percentage looks to build a commanding early lead. Pinewood struggled to find offensive rhythm against the Lions disciplined defense, and St. Andrews steadily extended the margin throughout the first half, taking full control of the game before the break.

The Lions maintained their intensity after halftime, continuing to defend, rebound, and share the ball effectively. Even with rotations and balanced lineups, St. Andrews never let the pace slip, closing out a complete wire-to-wire performance on the road.

Offensively, the Lions were led by JaCari Glover, Amari Cook, and Chase Brown, each of whom finished in double figures. Glover and Brown added six rebounds apiece, providing a strong presence on the glass, while Cook contributed five assists, directing the offense and creating opportunities for teammates throughout the night.

Perhaps most telling of the Lions performance was their balance, as 10 different players found the scoring column. The depth and unselfish play underscored a true team effort, with St. Andrews combining efficient shooting, interior dominance, and defensive consistency to open region play in emphatic fashion.

With the victory, the Lions took another confident step toward maintaining their region dominance, setting the tone early as they pursue yet another undefeated run through region competition.

RecapTitle: Lions Stay Hot With Win Over Savannah High

RecapTitle: Lions Roll Past Bulloch Academy, Remain Perfect in Region Play

RecapTitle: Lions Stay Perfect in Region Play With Home Win Over Westminster

RecapTitle: Lions Explode for 90 on Senior Night, Extend Streak Over Pinewood

RecapTitle: Lions Hold Off Late Surge at Frederica, Extend Streak
Recap:
